    <center><table class="itemDisplayTable">
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Title:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Stability Testing and a Review of Stabilization Methods of Two Dimensional Recursive Digital Filters</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Authors:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Ramesh .R</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Keywords:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Stability Testing<br />Two Dimensional Recursive</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Issue Date:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Nov-2008 </td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Publisher:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">SRM University</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Series/Report no.:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">T0003</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Abstract:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">The stability testing of two dimensional recursive digital filters had
been a classical problem for the last two decades. In literature there are two types
of methods for testing the stability of recursive digital filter. They are algebraic
and mapping methods. Even though the algebraic methods have a few practical
limitations in this implementation, stability can be determined in finite number
of steps. Even a low order filter requires large number of calculations. So this
method consumes very large time to find the exact stability. The accuracy of the
algebraic methods are affected by the finite word length of the computer.
The mapping methods can determine the stability, in infinite number
of steps. So mapping methods cannot guarantee the stability of the given
recursive digital filter in a finite number of steps. Jury’s row and column
algorithms in the mapping method have been considered as highly efficient, even
though they still run short of accuracy due to the length of the FFT used. If L is
the length of the FFT used and L = 1024, the number of one dimensional
polynomials with complex coefficients to be tested for stability is 513 (L/2 +1).
Then only one can reasonably arrive at a decision regarding the stability of the
given second order two dimensional recursive digital filter. So the best method is
not yet available, though some researchers have been working on this problem
even now.
The main aim of the research is to find the right solution for testing
the stability of two dimensional second order recursive digital filters. In this
thesis a new algebraic test procedure for one dimensional recursive digital filter
and restricted order (second) of two dimensional quarter-plane recursive digital
filter is proposed. In this method, it is assumed that the given transfer function is
vi
devoid of non-essential singularities of second kind. This stability testing method
is based on the evaluation of complex integrals.
This method is also extended to the second order Non-Symmetric
Half Plane (NSHP) filters and general two dimensional recursive digital filters.
This method gives best solution for barely stable or barely unstable recursive
digital filters, primarily of second order. Procedure for this method is very
simple. As it is an algebraic method it definitely takes more computational time
in comparison with the Anderson and Jury’s algebraic method. One important
advantage of the proposed method is that it provides the value of ΣΣh2(m,n)
(variance), for a stable filter, which is useful in finding out the quantization
error.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">URI:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/9432">http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/9432</a></td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Appears in Collections:</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="/dspace/handle/123456789/6855">Ph.D - Thesis  </a><br/></td></tr>
</table></center><br/>
